        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose for ALMA polarimetric observations in the full Stokes
mode, in order to achieve morphology of magnetic fields in angular
sizes up to 0.5", which is provided by the C34-4 configuration.  As
these two targets are nearby each other, relatively efficient
observations are possible: they can be observed in the same Science
Goal, sharing calibrators.  The object sizes are about 10" in our
CARMA observations with 5" angular resolution.  Therefore, it is
about a third of the field of view at Band 6.  Note that at the
proposed high angular resolution, the target will be smaller so
that the limitation of polarimetric observations in this proposal
call (only capable for compact objects smaller than a third of the
field of view) is satisfied.

The object peaks are 140 and 210 mJy/beam at 1.3 mm continuum in
our 5" CARMA data, respectively.  Based on our high angular resolution
CARMA data (Tobin et al. in prep) and Lee et al. (2009), the peak
intensities at the proposed ALMA angular resolution (0.5") are
expected as about 30 and 90 mJy/beam.  The polarization fraction
is about a few percent, so we plan to achieve 0.02 mJy/beam of a
sensitivity, in order to obtain at least 15 S/N polarization detection
toward the peaks.  This sensitivity will provide significant
polarization detection higher than 3 sigma level over at least 5
by 5 beam area.  The total time estimate in the ALMA Observing Tool
is 3 hours for both target observations together including all the
overheads.

The declinations of our targets are about 30 degree, which are at
a low elevation (about 37 degree) at the ALMA site. However, there
is no significant shadowing in the proposed C34-4 configuration,
and we emphasize that these two targets are the best in terms of
their previous polarization detection strength, magnetic field
morphology in large scales, extended continuum features in small
scales, and inclination.  The observations will be carried out at
the same frequency to our CARMA data.  Therefore, the ALMA data
will also be able to be combined with our CARMA data, which provides
us a unique data set sensitive to a very broad range of scales from
20" to 0.5".</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
